1 Fitting Gaussian and Student’s t ARMA(1,1) model

Simulating some data

set.seed(12345)
n =400
sig=1.0
nu=4
phi=0.98
theta=-0.64
tau = sqrt((nu-2)/nu)*sig
e.n = sig*rnorm(n)
e.t = tau*rt(n,df=nu)
y.n = rep(0,n)
y.t = rep(0,n)
y.n[1] = e.n[1]
y.t[1] = e.t[1]
for (t in 2:n){
y.n[t] = phi*y.n[t-1]+e.n[t]+theta*e.n[t-1]
y.t[t] = phi*y.t[t-1]+e.t[t]+theta*e.t[t-1]
}

## Plotting 
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
ts.plot(cbind(y.n,y.t),col=1:2,main="ARMA(1,1) data")
legend("bottomleft",legend=c("Gaussian","Student’s t"),col=1:2,lty=1,bty="n")

2 Maximum likelihood inference.

Using R function “nlm” to minimize the negative of the likelihood functions for both models.

## Preparing the data
y.n_1 <- rep(0,n)
y.n_1[2:400] <- y.n[1:399]
e.n_1 <- rep(0,n)
e.n_1[2:400] <- e.n[1:399]

y.t_1 <- rep(0,n)
y.t_1[2:400] <- y.t[1:399]
e.t_1 <- rep(0,n)
e.t_1[2:400] <- e.t[1:399]

## Negative of the loglikelihood functions
negllike.norm <-  function(thetas){-sum(dnorm((y.n-thetas[1]*y.n_1-thetas[2]*e.n_1)/sqrt(thetas[3]),log = TRUE)-log(sqrt(thetas[3])))}

logdt = function(m,s){dt((y.t-m)/sqrt(s),4,log=TRUE)-log(sqrt(s))}
negllike.t = function(thetas){-sum(logdt(thetas[1]*y.t_1+thetas[2]*e.t_1,thetas[3]))}

## nlm function
mle.norm <- nlm(negllike.norm,thetas <- c(0,0,1))
mle.t <- nlm(negllike.t,thetas <- c(0,0,1))

3 Bayesian inference via Monte Carlo methods.

  1. Now we will use sampling importance resampling (SIR) to sample from both posterior distributions of \(\theta\) \[ \begin{array}{l} p\left(\theta \mid y^{n}, \mathcal{M}_{0}\right) \propto \mathcal{L}\left(\theta \mid y^{n}, \mathcal{M}_{0}\right) p(\theta) \\ p\left(\theta \mid y^{n}, \mathcal{M}_{1}\right) \propto \mathcal{L}\left(\theta \mid y^{n}, \mathcal{M}_{1}\right) p(\theta) \end{array} \] First of all, I’ll define the likelihood, prior and proposal functions.

Notation: In the whole exercise we will be working with two models and two different DGPs. I’ll use “yt” and “yn” at the end of the function/object to make clear which model/GDP I am using. For example, “like.norm” means the likelihood of the normal distribution considering y.n and “like.norm.yt” means the likelihood of the normal distribution considering y.t. The same works for Student’s t distribution.

## Normal distribution functions
set.seed(12345)
like.norm    = function(phi,gamma,sig){prod(dnorm(y.n,phi*y.n_1+gamma*e.n_1,sig))}
like.norm.yt    = function(phi,gamma,sig){prod(dnorm(y.t,phi*y.t_1+gamma*e.t_1,sig))}
prior.norm   = function(phi,gamma,sig){dunif(phi,-1,1)*dunif(gamma,-1,1)*1/dgamma(sig^2,5/2,5*(1.4)/2)}
prop.norm    = function(phi,gamma,sig){dunif(phi,-1,1)*dunif(gamma,-1,1)*dunif(sig,.5,5)}

## t distribution functions
like.t    = function(phi,gamma,sig){prod(dt((y.t-phi*y.t_1-gamma*e.t_1)/sig,df=4)/sig)}
like.t.yn    = function(phi,gamma,sig){prod(dt((y.n-phi*y.n_1-gamma*e.n_1)/sig,df=4)/sig)}
prior.t   = function(phi,gamma,sig){dunif(phi,-1,1)*dunif(gamma,-1,1)*1/dgamma(sig^2,5/2,5*(1.4)/2)}
prop.t    = function(phi,gamma,sig){dunif(phi,-1,1)*dunif(gamma,-1,1)*dunif(sig,.5,5)}


## Drawing from the proposal
M <- 100000
draws.phi = runif(M,-1,1)
draws.gamma = runif(M,-1,1)
draws.sig = runif(M,0.5,5)

## Computing values - Normal distribution
likenn = rep(0,M)
for (i in 1:M){
  likenn[i] = like.norm(draws.phi[i],draws.gamma[i],draws.sig[i])
}

likenn.yt = rep(0,M)
for (i in 1:M){
  likenn.yt[i] = like.norm.yt(draws.phi[i],draws.gamma[i],draws.sig[i])
}
priorn = prior.norm(draws.phi,draws.gamma,draws.sig)
propn  = prop.norm(draws.phi,draws.gamma,draws.sig)

## Computing values - Student's t distribution
likent = rep(0,M)
for (i in 1:M){
  likent[i] = like.t(draws.phi[i],draws.gamma[i],draws.sig[i])
}

likent.yn = rep(0,M)
for (i in 1:M){
  likent.yn[i] = like.t.yn(draws.phi[i],draws.gamma[i],draws.sig[i])
}
priort = prior.t(draws.phi,draws.gamma,draws.sig)
propt  = prop.t(draws.phi,draws.gamma,draws.sig)

## Weights - Normal distribution
w = likenn*priorn/propn
w <- w/sum(w)

w.yt <- likenn.yt*priorn/propn
w.yt <- w.yt/sum(w.yt)

## Weights - Student's t distribution
wt = likent*priort/propt
wt <- wt/sum(wt)

wt.yn <- likent.yn*priort/propt
wt.yn <- wt.yn/sum(wt.yn)

## Resampling - Normal distribution
ind = sample(1:M,size=M,replace=TRUE,prob=w)
phi1 = draws.phi[ind] 
gamma1 = draws.gamma[ind]
sig1 = draws.sig[ind]

ind = sample(1:M,size=M,replace=TRUE,prob=w.yt)
phi1.yt = draws.phi[ind] 
gamma1.yt = draws.gamma[ind]
sig1.yt = draws.sig[ind]

## Resampling - Student's t distribution
indt = sample(1:M,size=M,replace=TRUE,prob=wt)
phi1t = draws.phi[indt] 
gamma1t = draws.gamma[indt]
sig1t = draws.sig[indt]

indt = sample(1:M,size=M,replace=TRUE,prob=wt.yn)
phi1t.yn = draws.phi[indt] 
gamma1t.yn = draws.gamma[indt]
sig1t.yn = draws.sig[indt]
  1. Computing posterior means, medians and 95% credibility interval for \(\phi, \gamma\) and \(\sigma^2\).

  1. Plotting the contours of the posterior density.
N      = 100
phis = seq(0.8,1.1,length=N)
gammas = seq(-0.8,-0.4,length=N)

liken <- matrix(0,N,N)
liken.yt <- matrix(0,N,N)
liket <- matrix(0,N,N)
liket.yn <- matrix(0,N,N)


## Filling matrix for gaussian and student's t distribution
for (i in 1:N)
  for (j in 1:N){
    liken[i,j] = like.norm(phis[i],gammas[j],mean(sig1))
  }

for (i in 1:N)
  for (j in 1:N){
    liken.yt[i,j] = like.norm.yt(phis[i],gammas[j],mean(sig1))
  }

for (i in 1:N)
  for (j in 1:N){
    liket[i,j] = like.t(phis[i],gammas[j],mean(sig1t))
  }

for (i in 1:N)
  for (j in 1:N){
    liket.yn[i,j] = like.t.yn(phis[i],gammas[j],mean(sig1t))
  }

## Contours
contour(phis,gammas,liken,drawlabels=FALSE,
        xlab=expression(phi),ylab=expression(gamma),
        main="Contours (Normal dist and y.n)")
points(phi.mle.norm,gamma.mle.norm,col=2,pch=16)

4 Prior predictive, Bayes factor and posterior model probability.

  1. Computing both prior predictive densities \[ p\left(y^{n} \mid \mathcal{M}_{j}\right)=\int_{0}^{\infty} \int_{-1}^{1} \int_{-1}^{1} \prod_{t=1}^{n} p\left(y_{t} \mid y_{t-1}, \theta, \mathcal{M}_{j}\right) d \phi d \gamma d \sigma^{2} \] via Monte Carlo by \[ \widehat{p}\left(y^{n} \mid \mathcal{M}_{j}\right)=\frac{1}{M} \sum_{i=1}^{M} p\left(y_{t} \mid y_{t-1}, \phi^{(i)}, \gamma^{(i)}, \sigma^{2(i)} \mathcal{M}_{j}\right) \] where \(\theta^{(1)},...,\theta^{(M)}\) are the draws from the prio \(p(\theta)\).
M <- 100000
phi = runif(M,-1,1)
gamma = runif(M,-1,1)
sig = runif(M,0.5,5)


## Functions used here are the ones calculated in item 2, considering the same especifications.
prob.n <- mean(likenn*prior.norm(phi,gamma,sig))
print(paste("Prior predictive normal dist and y.n= ",prob.n,sep=""))
## [1] "Prior predictive normal dist and y.n= 1.53636861842861e-224"
prob.n.yt <- mean(likenn.yt*prior.norm(phi,gamma,sig))
print(paste("Prior predictive normal dist and y.t= ",prob.n.yt,sep=""))
## [1] "Prior predictive normal dist and y.t= 1.02887799405382e-228"
prob.t <- mean(likent*prior.t(phi,gamma,sig))
print(paste("Prior predictive Student's t dist and y.t= ",prob.t,sep=""))
## [1] "Prior predictive Student's t dist and y.t= 4.17303703531737e-205"
prob.t.yn <- mean(likent.yn*prior.t(phi,gamma,sig))
print(paste("Prior predictive Student's t dist and y.n = ",prob.t.yn,sep=""))
## [1] "Prior predictive Student's t dist and y.n = 6.1600561812838e-231"
  1. Monte Carlo approximation to the Bayes factor for the gaussian model
BF01   = prob.n/prob.t.yn
print(paste("Bayes factor normal vs student's t = ",round(BF01,3),sep=""))
## [1] "Bayes factor normal vs student's t = 2494082.153"

Monte Carlo approximation to the Bayes factor for the Student’s t model

BF01.t   = prob.t/prob.n.yt
print(paste("Bayes factor normal vs student's t = ",round(BF01.t,3),sep=""))
## [1] "Bayes factor normal vs student's t = 4.05591047668872e+23"
  1. Calculating the posterior model probability of the Gaussian model.
PMP.n       = prob.n/(prob.n+prob.t.yn)
print(paste("Posterior model probability for Gaussian model = ",PMP.n,sep=""))
## [1] "Posterior model probability for Gaussian model = 0.999999599051059"

Based on the results calculated above, the evidence from the data to the model with gaussian distribution is quite superior, resulting in a Bayes factor close to 1.
